# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-capture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A **digital camera**, also called a **digicam**, is a camera that uses digital storage to capture images.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most cameras produced since the start of the 21st century are digital, largely replacing cameras that captured images on photographic film or film stock.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras are now integrated into mobile devices such as smartphones.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] However, high-end dedicated digital cameras are still commonly used by professionals.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras typically use a lens with an alterable diaphragm to focus light.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The diaphragm and shutter work to admit a controlled amount of light to the image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This process is the same as previously-used film cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] However, digital cameras use an image pickup device that is electronic, compared to chemical.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Additionally, digital cameras can display images on a screen immediately after being recorded, and store and delete images from stored memory.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras can also record moving videos with sound.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some digital cameras have the ability to crop and stitch pictures and perform other kinds of image editing.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), invented by Willard S.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Smith at Bell Labs in 1969, based on MOS capacitor technology.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The NMOS active-pixel sensor was later invented by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985, which led to the development of the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Lally of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory was thinking about how to use a mosaic photo sensor to capture digital images.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] His idea was to take pictures of the planets and stars while travelling through space to give information about the astronauts' position.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] As with Texas Instruments employee Willis Adcock's filmless camera (US patent 4,057,830) in 1972, the technology had yet to catch up with the concept.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 1972, the Landsat 1 satellite's multispectral scanner (MSS) started taking digital images of Earth.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The MSS, designed by Virginia Norwood at Hughes Aircraft Company starting in 1969, captured and transmitted image data from green, red, and two infrared bands with 6 bits per channel, using a mechanical rocking mirror and an array of 24 detectors.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Operating for six years, it transmitted more than 300,000 digital photographs of Earth while orbiting the planet about 14 times per day.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Also in 1972, Thomas McCord from MIT and James Westphal from Caltech together developed a digital camera for use with telescopes.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Their 1972 "photometer-digitizer system" used an analog-to-digital converter and a digital frame memory to store 256 x 256-pixel images of planets and stars, which were then recorded on digital magnetic tape.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] CCD sensors were not yet commercially available, and the camera used a silicon diode vidicon tube detector, which was cooled using dry ice to reduce dark current, allowing exposure times of up to one hour.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Cromemco Cyclops was an all-digital camera introduced as a commercial product in 1975.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Its design was published as a hobbyist construction project in the February 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* magazine.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It used a 32×32 metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, which was a modified MOS dynamic RAM (DRAM) memory chip.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Steven Sasson, an engineer at Eastman Kodak, built a self-contained electronic camera that used a monochrome Fairchild Semiconductor CCD image sensor in 1975.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Around the same time, Fujifilm began developing CCD technology in the 1970s.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Early uses were mainly military and scientific, followed by medical and news applications.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first filmless SLR (single lens reflex) camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Sony Mavica (magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3" format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analogue video signal processing and recording.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Mavica electronic still camera recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2" magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF".
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first electronic SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It employed an SLR viewfinder, included a 2/3" format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels, and was sold along with a removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Over the next few years, many other companies began selling SVF cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] These analog electronic cameras included the Nikon QV-1000C, which had an SLR viewfinder and a 2/3" format monochrome CCD sensor with 380K pixels and recorded analog black-and-white images on a Still Video Floppy.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] At Photokina 1988, Fujifilm introduced the FUJIX DS-1P, the first fully digital camera, which recorded digital images using a semiconductor memory card.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The camera's memory card had a capacity of 2 MB of SRAM (static random-access memory) and could hold up to ten photographs.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 1989, Fujifilm released the FUJIX DS-X, the first fully digital camera to be commercially released.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 1996, Toshiba's 40 MB flash memory card was adopted for several digital cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first prototype camera phones were included in Isaac (camera phone), a personal digital assistant for people with intellectual disabilities which was deployed in 1994.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first commercially available camera phone was the Kyocera Visual Phone VP-210, released in Japan in May 1999.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It was called a "mobile videophone" at the time, and had a 110,000-pixel front-facing camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It stored up to 20 JPEG digital images, which could be sent over e-mail, or the phone could send up to two images per second over Japan's Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) cellular network.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Samsung SCH-V200, released in South Korea in June 2000, was also one of the first phones with a built-in camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It had a TFT liquid-crystal display (LCD) and stored up to 20 digital photos at 350,000-pixel resolution.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] However, it could not send the resulting image over the telephone function but required a computer connection to access photos.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first mass-market camera phone was the J-SH04, a Sharp J-Phone model sold in Japan in November 2000.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It could instantly transmit pictures via cell phone telecommunication.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] By the mid-2000s, higher-end cell phones had an integrated digital camera, and by the early 2010s, almost all smartphones had an integrated digital camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In the early 2020's, a revival of digital cameras produced from the early 2000s that were produced prior to smartphones occurred as a TikTok trend and spread to other online marketplaces such as eBay and Etsy.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The trend was characterized by Gen Z nostalgia and a homage to the Y2K aesthetic.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The two major types of digital image sensors are CCD and CMOS.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A CCD sensor has one amplifier for all the pixels, while each pixel in a CMOS active-pixel sensor has its own amplifier.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Compared to CCDs, CMOS sensors use less power.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with a small sensor use a back-side-illuminated CMOS (BSI-CMOS) sensor.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The image processing capabilities of the camera determine the outcome of the final image quality much more than the sensor type.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor that turns light into discrete signals.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The brighter the image at a given point on the sensor, the larger the value that is read for that pixel.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Depending on the physical structure of the sensor, a color filter array may be used, which requires demosaicing to recreate a full-color image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The number of pixels in the sensor determines the camera's "pixel count".
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In a typical sensor, the pixel count is the product of the number of rows and the number of columns.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] For example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares' resolution selector allows the user to optionally lower the resolution to reduce the file size per picture and extend lossless digital zooming.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The bottom resolution option is typically 640×480 pixels (0.3 megapixels).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] An image's sharpness is presented through the crisp detail, defined lines, and its depicted contrast.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Sharpness is a factor of multiple systems throughout the DSLR camera by its ISO, resolution, lens, and the lens settings, the environment of the image, and its post-processing.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Images have a possibility of being too sharp, but they can never be too in focus.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A digital camera resolution is determined by a digital sensor.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The digital sensor indicates a high level of sharpness can be produced through the amount of noise and grain that is tolerated through the lens of the camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Resolution within the field of digital stills and digital movies is indicated through the camera's ability to determine detail based on the distance, which is then measured by frame size, pixel type, number, and organization.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Although some DSLR cameras have limited resolutions, it is almost impossible to not have the proper sharpness for an image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The ISO choice when taking a photo affects the quality of the image, as high ISO settings equate to an image that is less sharp due to the increased amount of noise allowed into the image, along with too little noise, which can also produce an image that is not sharp.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Since the first digital backs were introduced, there have been three main methods of capturing the image, each based on the hardware configuration of the sensor and color filters.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The third method is called *scanning* because the sensor moves across the focal plane much like the sensor of an image scanner.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The *linear* or *tri-linear* sensors in scanning cameras use only a single line of photosensors, or three lines for the three colors.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Scanning may be accomplished by moving the sensor (for example, when using color co-site sampling) or by rotating the whole camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A digital rotating line camera offers images consisting of a total resolution that is very high.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Improvements in single-shot cameras and image file processing at the beginning of the 21st century made single-shot cameras almost completely dominant, even in high-end commercial photography.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most current consumer digital cameras use a Bayer filter mosaic in combination with an optical anti-aliasing filter to reduce the aliasing due to the reduced sampling of the different primary-color images.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A demosaicing algorithm is used to interpolate color information to create a full array of RGB image data.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Cameras that use a beam-splitter single-shot 3CCD approach, three-filter multi-shot approach, color co-site sampling or Foveon X3 sensor do not use anti-aliasing filters, nor demosaicing.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A single sensor element cannot simultaneously record these three intensities, so a color filter array (CFA) must be used to selectively filter a particular color for each pixel.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Bayer filter pattern is a repeating 2x2 mosaic pattern of light filters, with green ones at opposite corners and red and blue in the other two positions.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The high proportion of green takes advantage of the properties of the human visual system, which determines brightness mostly from green and is far more sensitive to brightness than to hue or saturation.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Sometimes a 4-color filter pattern is used, often involving two different hues of green.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] That provides potentially more accurate color, but requires a slightly more complicated interpolation process.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The color intensity values not captured for each pixel can be interpolated from the values of adjacent pixels which represent the color being calculated.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with digital image sensors that are smaller than the typical 35 mm film size have a smaller field or angle of view when used with a lens of the same focal length.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This is because the angle of view is a function of both focal length and the sensor or film size used.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The crop factor is relative to the 35mm film format.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] If a smaller sensor is used, as in most digicams, the field of view is cropped by the sensor to smaller than the 35 mm full-frame format's field of view.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This narrowing of the field of view may be described as crop factor, a factor by which a longer focal length lens would be needed to get the same field of view on a 35 mm film camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Full-frame digital SLRs use a sensor of the same size as a frame of 35 mm film.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Crop factors for non-SLR consumer compact and bridge cameras are larger, frequently 4x or more.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor which turns light into discrete signals.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] **Pixels are square and is often equal to 1**, for example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] On full-frame sensors (i.e., 24 mm 36 mm), some cameras propose images with 20–25 million pixels that were captured by 7.5–m photosites, or a surface that is 50 times larger.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras come in a wide range of sizes, prices, and capabilities.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In addition to general-purpose digital cameras, specialized cameras including multispectral imaging equipment and astrographs are used for scientific, military, medical, and other special purposes.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are intended to be portable (pocketable) and are particularly suitable for casual "snapshots".
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Point-and-shoot cameras usually fall under this category.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many incorporate a retractable lens assembly that provides optical zoom.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In most models, an auto-actuating lens cover protects the lens from elements.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most ruggedized or water-resistant models do not retract, and most with superzoom capability do not retract fully.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are usually designed to be easy to use.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Almost all include an automatic mode, or "auto mode", which automatically makes all camera settings for the user.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Compact digital cameras typically contain a small sensor that trades-off picture quality for compactness and simplicity; images can usually only be stored using lossy compression (JPEG).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most have a built-in flash usually of low power, sufficient for nearby subjects.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A few high-end compact digital cameras have a hot shoe for connecting to an external flash.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Live preview is almost always used to frame the photo on an integrated LCD.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In addition to being able to take still photographs almost all compact cameras have the ability to record video.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Compacts often have macro capability and zoom lenses, but the zoom range (up to 30x) is generally enough for candid photography but less than is available on bridge cameras (more than 60x), or the interchangeable lenses of DSLR cameras available at a much higher cost.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus systems in compact digital cameras generally are based on a contrast-detection methodology using the image data from the live preview feed of the main imager.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some compact digital cameras use a hybrid autofocus system similar to what is commonly available on DSLRs.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Typically, compact digital cameras incorporate a nearly silent leaf shutter into the lens but play a simulated camera sound for skeuomorphic purposes.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] For low cost and small size, the cameras typically use image sensor formats with a diagonal between 6 and 11 mm, corresponding to a crop factor between 7 and 4.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This gives them weaker low-light performance, greater depth of field, generally closer focusing ability, and smaller components than cameras using larger sensors.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some cameras use a larger sensor including, at the high end, a pricey full-frame sensor compact camera, such as Sony Cyber-shot DSC-RX1, but have the capability near that of a DSLR.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A variety of additional features are available depending on the model of the camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Such features include GPS, compass, barometers and altimeters.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Starting in 2010, some compact digital cameras can take 3D still photos.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] These 3D compact stereo cameras are able to capture 3D panoramic photos with dual lens or even a single lens for playback on a 3D TV.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, Sony released two add-on camera models without display, to be used with a smartphone or tablet, controlled by a mobile application via WiFi.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Rugged compact cameras typically include protection against submersion, hot and cold conditions, shock, and pressure.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Terms used to describe such properties include waterproof, freeze-proof, heatproof, shockproof, and crushproof, respectively.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Nearly all major camera manufacturers have at least one product in this category.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some are waterproof to a considerable depth up to 100 feet (30 m); others only 10 feet (3 m), but only a few will float.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Ruggeds often lack some of the features of ordinary compact camera, but they have video capability and the majority can record sound.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most have image stabilization and built-in flash.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Touchscreen LCD and GPS do not work underwater.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] GoPro and other brands offer action cameras which are rugged, small, and can be easily attached to helmets, arms, bicycles, etc.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most have a wide angle and fixed focus and can take still pictures and video, typically with sound.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The 360-degree camera can take picture or video 360 degrees using two lenses back-to-back and shooting at the same time.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some of the cameras are Ricoh Theta S, Nikon Keymission 360 and Samsung Gear 360.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Nico360 was launched in 2016 and claimed as the world's smallest 360-degree camera with size 46 x 46 x 28 mm (1.8 x 1.8 x 1.1 in) and price less than $200.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] With virtual reality mode built-in stitching, Wifi, and Bluetooth, live streaming can be done.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Due to it also being water resistant, the Nico360 can be used as action camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras physically resemble DSLRs, and are sometimes called DSLR-shape or DSLR-like.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] They provide some similar features but, like compacts, they use a fixed lens and a small sensor.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some compact cameras have also PSAM mode.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most use live preview to frame the image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Their usual autofocus is by the same contrast-detect mechanism as compacts, but many bridge cameras have a manual focus mode and some have a separate focus ring for greater control.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The big physical size and small sensor allow superzoom and wide aperture.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras generally include an image stabilization system to enable longer handheld exposures, sometimes better than DSLR for low light conditions.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Sony RX10) or 400 mm (variable aperture, e.g.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix FZ1000) equivalent, corresponding to an optical zoom factor of roughly 10 to 15.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some bridge cameras have a lens thread to attach accessories such as wide-angle or telephoto converters as well as filters such as UV or Circular Polarizing filter and lens hoods.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The scene is composed by viewing the display or the electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most have a slightly longer shutter lag than a DSLR.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many of these cameras can store images in a raw format in addition to supporting JPEG.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The majority have a built-in flash, but only a few have a hotshoe.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In bright sun, the quality difference between a good compact camera and a digital SLR is minimal but bridge cameras are more portable, cost less and have a greater zoom ability.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Thus a bridge camera may better suit outdoor daytime activities, except when seeking professional-quality photos.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In late 2008, a new type of camera emerged, called a *mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera*.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] It is technically a DSLR camera that does not require a reflex mirror, a key component of the former.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] While a typical DSLR has a mirror that reflects light from the lens up to the optical viewfinder, in a mirrorless camera, there is no optical viewfinder.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The image sensor is exposed to light at all times, giving the user a digital preview of the image either on the built-in rear LCD screen or an electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] These are simpler and more compact than DSLRs due to not having a lens reflex system.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some MILCs have a separate electronic viewfinder to compensate the lack of an optical one.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In other cameras, the back display is used as the primary viewfinder in the same way as in compact cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] One disadvantage of mirrorless cameras compared to a typical DSLR is its battery life due to the energy consumption of the electronic viewfinder, but this can be mitigated by a setting inside the camera in some models.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Olympus and Panasonic released many Micro Four-Thirds cameras with interchangeable lenses that are fully compatible with each other without any adapter, while others have proprietary mounts.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2014, Kodak released its first Micro Four Third system camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] As of March 2014, mirrorless cameras are fast becoming appealing to both amateurs and professionals alike due to their simplicity, compatibility with some DSLR lenses, and features that match most DSLRs today.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] While most digital cameras with interchangeable lenses feature a lens-mount of some kind, there are also a number of modular cameras, where the shutter and sensor are incorporated into the lens module.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The first such modular camera was the Minolta Dimâge V in 1996, followed by the Minolta Dimâge EX 1500 in 1998 and the Minolta MetaFlash 3D 1500 in 1999.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2009, Ricoh released the Ricoh GXR modular camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] At CES 2013, Sakar International announced the Polaroid iM1836, an 18MP camera with 1"-sensor with interchangeable sensor-lens.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] An adapter for Micro Four-Thirds, Nikon and K-mount lenses was planned to ship with the camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] There are also a number of add-on camera modules for smartphones, they are called *lens-style* cameras (lens camera or smart lens).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] They contain all the essential components of a digital camera inside a DSLR lens-shaped module, hence the name, but lack any sort of viewfinder and most controls of a regular camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Instead, they are connected wirelessly and/or mounted to a smartphone to be used as its display output and operate the camera's various controls.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR) is a camera with a digital sensor that uses a reflex mirror to split or direct light into the viewfinder to produce an image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The reflex mirror finds the image by blocking light to the camera's sensor and then reflecting it into the camera's pentaprism which allows it to be seen through the viewfinder.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] When the shutter release is fully pressed the reflex mirror pulls out horizontally below the pentaprism briefly darkening the viewfinder and then opening up the sensor for exposure which creates the photo.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The digital image is produced by the sensor which is an array of photoreceptors on a microchip capable of recording light values.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many modern DSLRs offer the ability for "live view" or the framing of the subject emitted from the sensor onto a digital screen, and many have a hotshoe.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The sensor also known as a **full-frame sensor** is much larger than the other types, typically 18mm to 36mm on the diagonal (crop factor 2, 1.6, or 1).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The larger sensor permits more light to be received by each pixel; this, combined with the relatively large lenses provides superior low-light performance.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] For the same field of view and the same aperture, a larger sensor gives shallower focus.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs can equip interchangeable lenses for versatility by removing it from the lens mount of the camera, typically a silver ring on the front side of DSLRs.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] These lenses work in tandem with the mechanics of the DSLR to adjust aperture and focus.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus is accomplished using sensors in the mirror box and on most modern lenses can be activated from the lens itself which will trigger upon shutter release.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2025, a variety of lower-cost medium format digital cameras were available in the 50 to 100MP resolution range.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Digital Still Camera (DSC), such as the Sony DSC cameras, is a type of camera that does not use a reflex mirror.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] DSCs are like point-and-shoot cameras and are the most common type of cameras, due to their comfortable price and its quality.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with fixed semi-transparent mirrors, also known as DSLT cameras, such as the Sony SLT cameras, are single-lens without a moving reflex mirror as in a conventional DSLR.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A semi-transparent mirror transmits some of the light to the image sensor and reflects some of the light along the path to an autofocus sensor.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The total amount of light is not changed, just some of the light travels one path and some of it travels the other.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The consequences are that DSLT cameras should shoot a half stop differently from DSLR.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] One advantage of using a DSLT camera is the blind moments a DSLR user experiences while the reflecting mirror is moved to send the light to the sensor instead of the viewfinder.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The "blackouts" do not exist for DSLT cameras since they use an EVF (electronic viewfinder).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Since there is no time at which light is not traveling along both paths, DSLT cameras get the benefit of continuous autofocus tracking.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This is especially beneficial for burst-mode shooting in low-light conditions and also for tracking when taking video.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A rangefinder is a device to measure subject distance, with the intent to adjust the focus of a camera's objective lens accordingly (open-loop controller).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The rangefinder and lens focusing mechanism may or may not be coupled.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In common parlance, the term "rangefinder camera" is interpreted very narrowly to denote manual-focus cameras with a visually-read out optical rangefinder based on parallax.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most digital cameras achieve focus through analysis of the image captured by the objective lens and distance estimation, if it is provided at all, is only a byproduct of the focusing process (closed-loop controller).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A line-scan camera traditionally has a single row of pixel sensors, instead of a matrix of them.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The lines are continuously fed to a computer that joins them to each other and makes an image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] That is most commonly done by connecting the camera output to a frame grabber which resides in a PCI slot of an industrial computer.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The frame grabber acts to buffer the image and sometimes provide some processing before delivering to the computer software for processing.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Industrial processes often require height and width measurements performed by digital line-scan systems.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Multiple rows of sensors may be used to make colored images, or to increase sensitivity by TDI (time delay and integration).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many industrial applications require a wide field of view.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Traditionally maintaining consistent light over large 2D areas is quite difficult.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] With a line scan camera all that is necessary is to provide even illumination across the "line" currently being viewed by the camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This makes sharp pictures of objects that pass the camera at high speed.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Such cameras are also commonly used to make photo finishes, to determine the winner when multiple competitors cross the finishing line at nearly the same time.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] They can also be used as industrial instruments for analyzing fast processes.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are also extensively used in imaging from satellites (see push broom scanner).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In this case the row of sensors is perpendicular to the direction of satellite motion.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are widely used in scanners.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In this case, the camera moves horizontally.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Superzoom cameras are cameras fitted with a variable focal length lens, typically ranging from a wide-angle focal length to a super-telephoto focal length.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This type of digital camera captures information about the light field emanating from a scene; that is the intensity of light in a scene, and also the direction that the light rays are traveling in space.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This contrasts with a conventional digital camera, which records only light intensity.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Instead of measuring the intensity of light over some predetermined time interval (the exposure time), event cameras detect when the intensity of light changes by some threshold for each pixel independently, usually with microsecond precision.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many devices have a built-in digital camera, including, for example, smartphones, mobile phones, PDAs and laptop computers.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Built-in cameras generally store the images in the JPEG file format, although cameras in Apple's iPhone line have used the HEIC format since 2017.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Mobile phones incorporating digital cameras were introduced in Japan in 2001 by J-Phone.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2003 camera phones outsold stand-alone digital cameras, and in 2006 they outsold film and digital stand-alone cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Five billion camera phones were sold in five years, and by 2007 more than half of the installed base of all mobile phones were camera phones.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Sales of separate cameras peaked in 2008.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Several manufacturers lead in digital camera (commonly DSLRs) production.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Each brand embodies different mission statements that differentiate it from the others besides the equipment it manufactures.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Most manufacturers share modern features in the cameras they produce.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] However, some specialize in specific details, either physically on camera or within the system and image quality.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Sales of traditional digital cameras have declined due to the increasing use of smartphones for casual photography, which also enable easier manipulation and sharing of photos through the use of apps and web-based services.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] "Bridge cameras", in contrast, have held their ground with functionality that most smartphone cameras lack, such as optical zoom and other advanced features.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs have also lost ground to Mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera (MILC)s offering the same sensor size in a smaller camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A few expensive ones use a full-frame sensor, just like DSLR professional cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In response to the convenience and flexibility of smartphone cameras, some manufacturers produced "smart" digital cameras that combine features of traditional cameras with those of a smartphone.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2012, Nikon and Samsung released the Coolpix S800c and Galaxy Camera, the first two digital cameras to run the Android operating system.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Since this software platform is used in many smartphones, they can integrate with some of the same services (such as e-mail attachments, social networks and photo sharing sites) that smartphones do and use other Android-compatible software.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In an inversion, some phone makers have introduced smartphones with cameras designed to resemble traditional digital cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Nokia released the 808 PureView and Lumia 1020 in 2012 and 2013; the two devices respectively run the Symbian and Windows Phone operating systems, and both include a 41-megapixel camera (along with a camera grip attachment for the latter).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Similarly, Samsung introduced the Galaxy S4 Zoom, having a 16-megapixel camera and 10x optical zoom, combining traits from the Galaxy S4 Mini with the Galaxy Camera.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix DMC-CM1 is an Android KitKat 4.4 smartphone with 20MP, 1" sensor, the largest sensor for a smartphone ever, with Leica fixed lens equivalent of 28 mm at F2.8, can take RAW image and 4K video, has 21 mm thickness.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Furthermore, in 2018 Huawei P20 Pro is an android Oreo 8.1 has triple Leica lenses in the back of the smartphone with 40MP 1/1.7" RGB sensor as first lens, 20MP 1/2.7" monochrome sensor as second lens and 8MP 1/4" RGB sensor with 3x optical zoom as third lens.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Combination of first lens and second lens will produce bokeh image with larger high dynamic range, whereas combination of mega pixel first lens and optical zoom will produce maximum 5x digital zoom without loss of quality by reducing the image size to 8MP.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] After a big dip of sales in 2012, consumer digital camera sales declined again in 2013 by 36 percent.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2011, compact digital cameras sold 10 million per month.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, sales fell to about 4 million per month.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] DSLR and MILC sales also declined in 2013 by 10–15% after almost ten years of double digit growth.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Worldwide unit sales of digital cameras is continuously declining from 148 million in 2011 to 58 million in 2015 and tends to decrease more in the following years.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Film camera sales hit their peak at about 37 million units in 1997, while digital camera sales began in 1989.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] By 2008, the film camera market had died and digital camera sales hit their peak at 121 million units in 2010.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2002, cell phones with an integrated camera had been introduced and in 2003 the cell phone with an integrated camera had sold 80 million units per year.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] By 2011, cell phones with an integrated camera were selling hundreds of millions per year, which were causing a decline in digital cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In 2015, digital camera sales were 35 million units or only less than a third of digital camera sales numbers at their peak and also slightly less than film camera sold number at their peak.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] A common alternative is the use of a card reader which may be capable of reading several types of storage media, as well as high speed transfer of data to the computer.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Use of a card reader also avoids draining the camera battery during the download process.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] An external card reader allows convenient direct access to the images on a collection of storage media.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] But if only one storage card is in use, moving it back and forth between the camera and the reader can be inconvenient.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many computers have a card reader built in, at least for SD cards.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many modern cameras support the PictBridge standard, which allows them to send data directly to a PictBridge-capable printer without the need for a computer.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] PictBridge uses PTP to transfer images and control information.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Wireless connectivity can also provide for printing photos without a cable connection.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] An *instant-print camera*, is a digital camera with a built-in printer.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] This confers a similar functionality as an instant camera which uses instant film to quickly generate a physical photograph.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Such non-digital cameras were popularized by Polaroid with the SX-70 in 1972.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras include a video output port.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Usually sVideo, it sends a standard-definition video signal to a television, allowing the user to show one picture at a time.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Buttons or menus on the camera allow the user to select the photo, advance from one to another, or automatically send a "slide show" to the TV.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] HDMI has been adopted by many high-end digital camera makers, to show photos in their high-resolution quality on an HDTV.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] In January 2008, Silicon Image announced a new technology for sending video from mobile devices to a television in digital form.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] MHL sends pictures as a video stream, up to 1080p resolution, and is compatible with HDMI.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some DVD recorders and television sets can read memory cards used in cameras; alternatively several types of flash card readers have TV output capability.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Cameras can be equipped with a varying amount of environmental sealing to provide protection against splashing water, moisture (humidity and fog), dust and sand, or complete waterproofness to a certain depth and for a certain duration.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The latter is one of the approaches to allow underwater photography, the other approach being the use of waterproof housings.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many waterproof digital cameras are also shockproof and resistant to low temperatures.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Some waterproof cameras can be fitted with a waterproof housing to increase the operational depth range.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] The Olympus 'Tough' range of compact cameras is an example.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras have preset modes for different applications.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Within the constraints of correct exposure various parameters can be changed, including exposure, aperture, focusing, light metering, white balance, and equivalent sensitivity.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] For example, a portrait might use a wider aperture to render the background out of focus, and would seek out and focus on a human face rather than other image content.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Few cameras are equipped with a voice note (audio-only) recording feature.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares may be equipped with the ability to select a suitable scene mode automatically through artificial intelligence.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Many camera phones and most stand alone digital cameras store image data in flash memory cards or other removable media.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Most stand-alone cameras use SD format, while a few use CompactFlash, CFexpress or other types.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] In January 2012, a faster XQD card format was announced.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] In early 2014, some high end cameras have two hot-swappable memory slots.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Photographers can swap one of the memory card with camera-on.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Each memory slot can accept either Compact Flash or SD Card.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] All new Sony cameras also have two memory slots, one for its Memory Stick and one for SD Card, but not hot-swapable.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The approximate count of remaining photos until space exhaustion is calculated by the firmware throughout use and indicated in the viewfinder, to prepare the user for an impending necessary hot swap of the memory card, and/or file offload.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] A few cameras used other removable storage such as Microdrives (very small hard disk drives), CD single (185 MB), and 3.5" floppy disks (e. g.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Most manufacturers of digital cameras do not provide drivers and software to allow their cameras to work with Linux or other free software.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Still, many cameras use the standard USB mass storage and/or Media Transfer Protocol, and are thus widely supported.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Other cameras are supported by the gPhoto project, and many computers are equipped with a memory card reader.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The Joint Photography Experts Group standard (JPEG) is the most common file format for storing image data.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Other file types include Tagged Image File Format (TIFF), High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF), and various Raw image formats.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Many cameras, especially high-end ones, support a raw image format.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] A raw image is the unprocessed set of pixel data directly from the camera's sensor, often saved in a proprietary format.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Adobe Systems has released the DNG format, a royalty-free raw image format used by at least 10 camera manufacturers.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Raw files initially had to be processed in specialized image editing programs, but over time many mainstream editing programs, such as Google's Picasa, have added support for raw images.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Rendering to standard images from raw sensor data allows more flexibility in making major adjustments without losing image quality or retaking the picture.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Formats for movies are AVI, DV, MPEG, MOV (often containing motion JPEG), WMV, and ASF (basically the same as WMV).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Recent formats include MP4, which is based on the QuickTime format and uses newer compression algorithms to allow longer recording times in the same space.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Other formats that are used in cameras (but not for pictures) are the Design Rule for Camera Format (DCF), an ISO specification, used in almost all camera since 1998, which defines an internal file structure and naming.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Also used is the Digital Print Order Format (DPOF), which dictates what order images are to be printed in and how many copies.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The DCF 1998 defines a logical file system with 8.3 filenames and makes the usage of either FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT mandatory for its physical layer to maximize platform interoperability.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Most cameras include Exif data that provides metadata about the picture.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Exif data may include aperture, exposure time, focal length, date and time taken.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] To guarantee interoperability, DCF specifies the file system for image and sound files to be used on formatted DCF media (like removable or non-removable memory) as FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, or exFAT.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Media with a capacity of more than 2 GB must be formatted using FAT32 or exFAT.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] These directories contain files with names such as "ABCD1234.JPG" that consist of four alphanumeric characters (often "100_", "DSC0", "DSCF", "IMG_", "MOV_", or "P000"), followed by a number.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Handling of directories with possibly user-created duplicate numbers may vary among camera firmwares.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] DCF 2.0 adds support for DCF optional files recorded in an optional color space (that is, Adobe RGB rather than sRGB).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Such files must be indicated by a leading "_" (as in "_DSC" instead of "100_" or "DSC0").
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] To enable loading many images in miniature view quickly and efficiently, and to retain meta data, some vendors' firmwares generate accompanying low-resolution thumbnail files for videos and raw photos.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For example, those of Canon cameras end with `.THM`.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] JPEG can already store a thumbnail image standalone.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras have become smaller over time, resulting in an ongoing need to develop a battery small enough to fit in the camera and yet able to power it for a reasonable length of time.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras use either proprietary or standard consumer batteries.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] As of March 2014, most cameras use proprietary lithium-ion batteries while some use standard AA batteries or primarily use a proprietary Lithium-ion rechargeable battery pack but have an optional AA battery holder available.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The most common class of battery used in digital cameras is proprietary battery formats.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] These are built to a manufacturer's custom specifications.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Almost all proprietary batteries are lithium-ion.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] In addition to being available from the OEM, aftermarket replacement batteries are commonly available for most camera models.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras which use off-the-shelf batteries are typically designed to be able to use both single-use disposable and rechargeable batteries, but not with both types in use at the same time.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The most common off-the-shelf battery size used is AA.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] CR2, CR-V3 batteries, and AAA batteries are also used in some cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The CR2 and CR-V3 batteries are lithium based, intended for a single use.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Rechargeable RCR-V3 lithium-ion batteries are also available as an alternative to non-rechargeable CR-V3 batteries.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Some battery grips for DSLRs come with a separate holder to accommodate AA cells as an external power source.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] When digital cameras became common, many photographers asked whether their film cameras could be converted to digital.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The answer was not immediately clear, as it differed among models.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For the majority of 35 mm film cameras the answer is no, the reworking and cost would be too great, especially as lenses have been evolving as well as cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For most a conversion to digital, to give enough space for the electronics and allow a liquid crystal display to preview, would require removing the back of the camera and replacing it with a custom built digital unit.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Many early professional SLR cameras, such as the Kodak DCS series, were developed from 35 mm film cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The technology of the time, however, meant that rather than being digital "backs" the bodies of these cameras were mounted on large, bulky digital units, often bigger than the camera portion itself.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] These were factory built cameras, however, not aftermarket conversions.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] A notable exception is the Nikon E2 and Nikon E3, using additional optics to convert the 35 mm format to a 2/3 CCD-sensor.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] A few 35 mm cameras have had digital camera backs made by their manufacturer, Leica being a notable example with the Leica R8–R9.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Medium format and large format cameras (those using film stock greater than 35 mm), have a low unit production, and typical digital backs for them cost over $10,000.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] These cameras also tend to be highly modular, with handgrips, film backs, winders, and lenses available separately to fit various needs.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The very large sensor these backs use leads to enormous image sizes.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One's P45 39 MP image back creates a single TIFF image of size up to 224.6 MB, and even greater pixel counts are available.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Medium format digitals such as this are geared more towards studio and portrait photography than their smaller DSLR counterparts; the ISO speed in particular tends to have a maximum of 400, versus 6400 for some DSLR cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] (Canon EOS-1D Mark IV and Nikon D3S have ISO 12800 plus Hi-3 ISO 102400 with the Canon EOS-1Dx's ISO of 204800).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] In the industrial and high-end professional photography market, some camera systems use modular (removable) image sensors.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For example, some medium format SLR cameras, such as the Mamiya 645D series, allow installation of either a digital camera back or a traditional photographic film back.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Linear array cameras are also called scan backs.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Most earlier digital camera backs used linear array sensors, moving vertically to digitize the image.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Many of them only capture grayscale images.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The relatively long exposure times, in the range of seconds or even minutes generally limit scan backs to studio applications, where all aspects of the photographic scene are under the photographer's control.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Some other camera backs use CCD arrays similar to typical cameras.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Since it is much easier to manufacture a high-quality linear CCD array with only thousands of pixels than a CCD matrix with millions, very high resolution linear CCD camera backs were available much earlier than their CCD matrix counterparts.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For example, you could buy an (albeit expensive) camera back with over 7,000 pixel horizontal resolution in the mid-1990s.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] However, as of 2004, it is still difficult to buy a comparable CCD matrix camera of the same resolution.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Rotating line cameras, with about 10,000 color pixels in its sensor line, are able, as of 2005, to capture about 120,000 lines during one full 360-degree rotation, thereby creating a single digital image of 1,200 Megapixels.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] Most modern digital camera backs use CCD or CMOS matrix sensors.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] The matrix sensor captures the entire image frame at once, instead of incrementing scanning the frame area through the prolonged exposure.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One produces a 39 million pixel digital camera back with a 49.1 × 36.8 mm CCD in 2008.
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] This CCD array is a little smaller than a frame of 120 film and much larger than a 35 mm frame (36 × 24 mm).
[src:image-capture/digital-camera-p02] In comparison, consumer digital cameras use arrays ranging from 36 × 24 mm (full frame on high end consumer DSLRs) to 1.28 × 0.96 mm (on camera phones) CMOS sensor.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] The **`grabFrame()`** method of the `ImageCapture` interface takes a snapshot of the live video in a `MediaStreamTrack` and returns a `Promise` that resolves with an `ImageBitmap` containing the snapshot.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] A `Promise` that resolves to an `ImageBitmap` object.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] Thrown if `readyState` property of the `MediaStreamTrack` passing in the constructor is not `live`.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] Thrown if the operation can't complete for any reason.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] This example is extracted from this Simple Image Capture demo.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] It shows how to use the `Promise` returned by `grabFrame()` to copy the returned frame to a `<canvas>` element.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-grabframe] For simplicity it does not show how to instantiate the `ImageCapture` object.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] The **`takePhoto()`** method of the `ImageCapture` interface takes a single exposure using the video capture device sourcing a `MediaStreamTrack` and returns a `Promise` that resolves with a `Blob` containing the data.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] An object that sets options for the photo to be taken.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] The flash setting of the capture device, one of `"auto"`, `"off"`, or `"flash"`.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] The user agent selects the closest height value to this setting if it only supports discrete heights.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] The user agent selects the closest width value to this setting if it only supports discrete widths.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] A boolean indicating whether the red-eye reduction should be used if it is available.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] A `Promise` that resolves with a `Blob`.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture-takephoto] It shows how to use the `Promise` returned by `takePhoto()` to copy the returned `Blob` to an `<img>` element.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] The **`ImageCapture`** interface of the MediaStream Image Capture API provides methods to enable the capture of images or photos from a camera or other photographic device.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] It provides an interface for capturing images from a photographic device referenced through a valid `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Creates a new `ImageCapture` object which can be used to capture still frames (photos) from a given `MediaStreamTrack` which represents a video stream.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Returns a reference to the `MediaStreamTrack` passed to the constructor.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Takes a single exposure using the video capture device sourcing a `MediaStreamTrack` and returns a `Promise` that resolves with a `Blob` containing the data.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object containing the ranges of available configuration options.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object containing the current photo configuration settings.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Takes a snapshot of the live video in a `MediaStreamTrack`, returning an `ImageBitmap`, if successful.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] The following code is taken from Chrome's Grab Frame - Take Photo Sample.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Since `ImageCapture` requires some place to capture an image from, the example below starts with a device's media device (in other words a camera).
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] This example shows, roughly, a `MediaStreamTrack` extracted from a device's `MediaStream`.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] The track is then used to create an `ImageCapture` object so that `takePhoto()` and `grabFrame()` can be called.
[src:image-capture/imagecapture] Finally, it shows how to apply the results of these calls to a canvas object.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] The **`MediaStreamTrack`** interface of the Media Capture and Streams API represents a single media track within a stream; typically, these are audio or video tracks, but other track types may exist as well.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Some user agents subclass this interface to provide more precise information or functionality, such as `CanvasCaptureMediaStreamTrack`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] In addition to the properties listed below, `MediaStreamTrack` has constrainable properties which can be set using `applyConstraints()` and accessed using `getConstraints()` and `getSettings()`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] See Capabilities, constraints, and settings to learn how to correctly work with constrainable properties.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Not doing so correctly will result in your code being unreliable.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] A string that may be used by the web application to provide a hint as to what type of content the track contains to guide how it should be treated by API consumers.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Allowable values depend on the value of the `MediaStreamTrack.kind` property.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] A Boolean whose value of `true` if the track is enabled, that is allowed to render the media source stream; or `false` if it is disabled, that is not rendering the media source stream but silence and blackness.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] If the track has been disconnected, this value can be changed but has no more effect.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a string containing a unique identifier (GUID) for the track; it is generated by the browser.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a string set to `"audio"` if the track is an audio track and to `"video"`, if it is a video track.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] It doesn't change if the track is disassociated from its source.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a string containing a user agent-assigned label that identifies the track source, as in `"internal microphone"`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] The string may be left empty and is empty as long as no source has been connected.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] When the track is disassociated from its source, the label is not changed.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the track is unable to provide media data due to a technical issue.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns an enumerated string giving the status of the track.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Lets the application specify the ideal and/or ranges of acceptable values for any number of the available constrainable properties of the `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a duplicate of the `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns an object detailing the accepted values or value range for each constrainable property of the associated `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a `MediaTrackConstraints` object containing the currently set constraints for the track; the returned value matches the constraints last set using `applyConstraints()`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Returns a `MediaTrackSettings` object containing the current values of each of the `MediaStreamTrack`'s constrainable properties.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Stops playing the source associated to the track, both the source and the track are disassociated.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Sent when playback of the track ends (when the value `readyState` changes to `ended`), except when the track is ended by calling `MediaStreamTrack.stop`.
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Sent to the `MediaStreamTrack` when the value of the `muted` property is changed to `true`, indicating that the track is unable to provide data temporarily (such as when the network is experiencing a service malfunction).
[src:image-capture/mediastreamtrack] Sent to the track when data becomes available again, ending the `muted` state.
[src:image-capture/photograph] A **photograph** (also known as a **photo**, or more generically referred to as an *image* or *picture*) is an image created by light falling on a photosensitive surface, usually photographic film or an electronic image sensor.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The process and practice of creating such images is called photography.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Photographs are now created using a smartphone or camera, which uses a lens to focus the scene's visible wavelengths of light into a reproduction of what the human eye would perceive.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The word can refer either to the physical print—like a lithograph, serigraph, or photograph—or to the event itself, as in "she took a photograph", even before the image has been printed or viewed.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The first permanent photograph, a contact-exposed copy of an engraving, was made in 1822 using the bitumen-based "heliography" process developed by Nicéphore Niépce.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The first photographs of a real-world scene, made using a camera obscura, followed a few years later at Le Gras, France, in 1826, but Niépce's process was not sensitive enough to be practical for that application: a camera exposure lasting for hours or days was required.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In 1829, Niépce entered into a partnership with Louis Daguerre, and the two collaborated to work out a similar, but more sensitive, and otherwise improved process.
[src:image-capture/photograph] After Niépce's death on the 5th July 1833, Daguerre concentrated on silver halide-based alternatives.
[src:image-capture/photograph] He named this first practical process for making photographs with a camera, the daguerreotype, after himself.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Its existence was announced to the world on 7 January 1839, but working details were not made public until 19 August that year.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Other inventors soon made drastic improvements that reduced the required amount of exposure time from a few minutes to just a few seconds, making portrait photography truly practical and widely popular during this time.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The daguerreotype had shortcomings, notably the fragility of the mirror-like image surface and the particular viewing conditions required to see the image properly.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Each was a unique, opaque positive that could only be duplicated by copying it with a camera.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Inventors set about working out improved processes that would be more practical.
[src:image-capture/photograph] By the end of the 1850s, the daguerreotype had been replaced by the less expensive and more easily viewed ambrotype and tintype, which made use of the recently introduced collodion process.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Glass plate collodion negatives used to make prints on albumen paper soon became the preferred photographic method and held that position for many years, even after the introduction of the more convenient gelatin process in 1871.
[src:image-capture/photograph] It first became a widespread commercial reality with the introduction of Autochrome plates in 1907, but the plates were very expensive and not suitable for casual snapshot-taking with hand-held cameras.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The mid-1930s saw the introduction of Kodachrome and Agfacolor Neu, the first easy-to-use color films of the modern multi-layer chromogenic type.
[src:image-capture/photograph] These early processes produced transparencies for use in slide projectors and viewing devices, but color prints became increasingly popular after the introduction of chromogenic color print paper in the 1940s.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The needs of the motion picture industry generated a number of special processes and systems, perhaps the best-known being the now-obsolete three-strip Technicolor process.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Non-digital photographs are produced with a two-step chemical process.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In the two-step process, the light-sensitive film captures a *negative* image (colors and lights/darks are inverted).
[src:image-capture/photograph] To produce a *positive* image, the negative is most commonly transferred ('printed') onto photographic paper.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Printing the negative onto transparent film stock is used to manufacture motion picture films.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Alternatively, the film is processed to invert the *negative* image, yielding positive transparency.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Such positive images are usually mounted in frames, called slides.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Before recent advances in digital photography, transparencies were widely used by professionals because of their sharpness and accuracy of color rendition.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Most photographs published in magazines were taken on color transparency film.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Originally, all photographs were monochromatic or hand-painted in color.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Although methods for developing color photos were available as early as 1861, they did not become widely available until the 1940s or 1950s, and even so, until the 1960s, most photographs were taken in black and white.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Since then, color photography has dominated popular photography, although black-and-white is still used, being easier to develop than color.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Panoramic format images can be taken with cameras like the Hasselblad Xpan on standard film.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Since the 1990s, panoramic photos have been available on the Advanced Photo System (APS) film.
[src:image-capture/photograph] APS has become less popular and has been discontinued.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The advent of the microcomputer and digital photography has led to the rise of digital prints.
[src:image-capture/photograph] These prints are created from stored graphic formats such as JPEG, TIFF, and RAW.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The types of printers used include inkjet printers, dye-sublimation printers, laser printers, and thermal printers.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Inkjet prints are sometimes given the coined name "Giclée".
[src:image-capture/photograph] The Web has been a popular medium for storing and sharing photos ever since the first photograph was published on the web by Tim Berners-Lee in 1992 (an image of the CERN house band Les Horribles Cernettes).
[src:image-capture/photograph] Today, popular sites such as Flickr, PhotoBucket, and 500px are used by millions of people to share their pictures.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The first "selfie", or self-portrait, was taken by Robert Cornelious back in 1839.
[src:image-capture/photograph] "Selfies" have become one of the most common photographs.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Ideal photograph storage involves placing each photo in an individual folder constructed from buffered, or acid-free paper.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Buffered paper folders are especially recommended in cases when a photograph was previously mounted onto poor quality material or using an adhesive that will lead to even more acid creation.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Store photographs measuring 8x10 inches or smaller vertically along the longer edge of the photo in the buffered paper folder, within a larger archival box, and label each folder with relevant information to identify it.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The rigid nature of the folder protects the photo from slumping or creasing, as long as the box is not packed too tightly or under filled.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Folder larger photos or brittle photos stacked flat within archival boxes with other materials of comparable size.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The most stable of plastics used in photo preservation, polyester, does not generate any harmful chemical elements, nor does it have any capability to absorb acids generated by the photograph itself.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Polyester sleeves and encapsulation have been praised for their ability to protect the photograph from humidity and environmental pollution, slowing the reaction between the item and the atmosphere.
[src:image-capture/photograph] However, the polyester just as frequently traps these elements next to the material it is intended to protect.
[src:image-capture/photograph] This is especially risky in a storage environment that experiences drastic fluctuations in humidity or temperature, leading to ferrotyping, or sticking of the photograph to the plastic.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Photographs sleeved or encapsulated in polyester cannot be stored vertically in boxes because they will slide down next to each other within the box, bending and folding, nor can the archivist write directly onto the polyester to identify the photograph.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Therefore, it is necessary to either stack polyester-protected photographs horizontally within a box, or bind them in a three-ring binder.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Stacking the photos horizontally within a flat box will greatly reduce ease of access, and binders leave three sides of the photo exposed to the effects of light and do not support the photograph evenly on both sides, leading to slumping and bending within the binder.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The plastic used for enclosures has been manufactured to be as frictionless as possible to prevent scratching photos during insertion to the sleeves.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Unfortunately, the slippery nature of the enclosure generates a build-up of static electricity, which attracts dust and lint particles.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The static can attract the dust to the inside of the sleeve, as well, where it can scratch the photograph.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Likewise, these components that aid in insertion of the photo, referred to as slip agents, can break down and transfer from the plastic to the photograph, where they deposit as an oily film, attracting further lint and dust.
[src:image-capture/photograph] At this time, there is no test to evaluate the long-term effects of these components on photographs.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In addition, the plastic sleeves can develop kinks or creases in the surface, which will scratch away at the emulsion during handling.
[src:image-capture/photograph] It is best to leave photographs lying flat on the table when viewing them.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Do not pick it up from a corner, or even from two sides and hold it at eye level.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Every time the photograph bends, even a little, this can break down the emulsion.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The very nature of enclosing a photograph in plastic encourages users to pick it up; users tend to handle plastic enclosed photographs less gently than non-enclosed photographs, simply because they feel the plastic enclosure makes the photo impervious to all mishandling.
[src:image-capture/photograph] As long as a photo is in its folder, there is no need to touch it; simply remove the folder from the box, lay it flat on the table, and open the folder.
[src:image-capture/photograph] If for some reason the researchers or archivists do need to handle the actual photo, perhaps to examine the verso for writing, they can use gloves if there appears to be a risk from oils or dirt on the hands.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Because daguerreotypes were rendered on a mirrored surface, many spiritualists also became practitioners of the new art form.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Spiritualists would claim that the human image on the mirrored surface was akin to looking into one's soul.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The spiritualists also believed that it would open their souls and let demons in.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Among some Muslims, it is makruh (disliked) to perform salah (worship) in a place decorated with photographs.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Photography and darkroom anomalies and artifacts sometimes lead viewers to believe that spirits or demons have been captured in photos.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Some have made a career out of taking pictures of "ghosts" or "spirits".
[src:image-capture/photograph] There are many instances where people believe photos will bring bad luck either to the person taking the picture or people captured in the photo.
[src:image-capture/photograph] For instance, that a photograph taken of a pregnant woman will bring bad luck to the baby in the womb, or that photos taken of a dead person will ensure that person is not successful in the afterlife.
[src:image-capture/photograph] The production or distribution of certain types of photograph has been forbidden under modern laws, such as those of government buildings, highly classified regions, private property, copyrighted works, children's genitalia, child pornography and less commonly pornography overall.
[src:image-capture/photograph] These laws vary greatly between jurisdictions.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In some public property owned by government, such as law courts, government buildings, libraries, civic centres and some of the museums in Hong Kong, photography is not allowed without permission from the government.
[src:image-capture/photograph] It is illegal to equip or take photographs and recording in a place of public entertainment, such as cinemas and indoor theaters.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In Hungary, from 15 March 2014 when the long-awaited Civil Code was published, the law re-stated what had been normal practice, namely, that a person had the right to refuse being photographed.
[src:image-capture/photograph] However, implied consent exists: it is not illegal to photograph a person who does not actively object.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In South Africa photographing people in public is legal.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Reproducing and selling photographs of people is legal for editorial and limited fair use commercial purposes.
[src:image-capture/photograph] There exists no case law to define what the limits on commercial use are.
[src:image-capture/photograph] In the United Kingdom there are no laws forbidding photography of private property from a public place.
[src:image-capture/photograph] Persistent and aggressive photography of a single individual may come under the legal definition of harassment.
[src:image-capture/photograph] A right to privacy came into existence in UK law as a consequence of the incorporation of the European Convention on Human Rights into domestic law through the Human Rights Act 1998.
[src:image-capture/photograph] This can result in restrictions on the publication of photography.
